text.tspan: Internet of things code deployment metrics
Ward Schodts & Xavier Gos Aguililla

flowRoot.flowPara: Current MO in WSN design: deploy all CPU & flash-intensive code to the backend tiers (gateways & servers) use motes purely for sensing and sending via radio.
Radio usage is very expensive, so this method of data processing eats up a lot of energy.
Since it is important to ensure the longevity of the sensors, maybe not the best approach.
Is it possible to offload some of the computation and storage to the sensor nodes themselves?
Concretely: can we find a simple metric which allows us to quickly assess in which tier we run code? this is the transmit/store/compute ratio

text.tspan: Blackbox
Whitebox
For the same type of sensing task:
manually create several code deployment scenarios.
Use the oscilloscope method to determine whether
computing or storing on the motes is useful.
Measure experimentally the atomic cost of CPU, flash & radio.
ex. radio cost per packet, flash cost per byte written,
CPU cost per time.
Develop a tool which maps the above data to real code.
input: a LooCi component
outputs: the requirements in transmission,
storage and computation
a ratio which can suggest the tier
on which to deploy the component code.
Supervised by prof. Danny Hughes & Klaas Thoelen
We expect that WSN energy consumption in general can benefit from deploying some code on the sensor tier,
if we keep in mind the limited resources of a typical mote. Experiments are still ongoing.
